The '''Ohio Department of Job and Family Services,''' (ODJFS), a department that employs 4,000 full-time employees, has an annual budget of more than $17 billion. ODJFS supervises the provision of [[Medicaid]], [[food stamps]], [[child welfare]] and [[child support]] in [[Ohio]]. Also, ODJFS provides services such as [[unemployment]] compensation to Ohio's citizens.<ref name ="ODJFS">{{cite web
|url=http://jfs.ohio.gov/ocomm_root/director.stm 
|date=2008
|accessdate = 2008-12-06
|title = Director, Ohio Department of Job and Family Services
|publisher = Ohio Department of Job and Family Services
}}</ref>

==History==
{{Expand-section|date=December 2008}}
On July 1, 2000, the Ohio Department of Human Services and the Ohio Bureau of Employment Services combined
to become the ODJFS.<ref name ="Learning From Leaders">{{cite web
|url= http://books.google.com/books?id=kN_41XK9k2EC&pg=PA15&dq=%22Ohio+Department+of+Job+and+Family+Services%22#PPA16,M1
|date=2008-12-05
|accessdate = 2008-12-08
|title = "Learning from Leaders"
|publisher = [[Rockefeller Institute]]
}}</ref> ODJFS oversees programs helping unborn babies and their mothers with health care issues while also helping unemployed workers and seniors citizens find food and shelter. <ref name ="Dayton daily news">{{cite web
|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/n/content/oh/story/news/local/2007/02/05/ddn020507joneskelley.html
|date=2007-02-05
|accessdate = 2008-12-10
|title = "Success would be the end of my job, director says"
|publisher = [[Dayton Daily News]]
}}</ref>

In December of 2004, the ODJFS and the Ohio auditor's office launched a joint audit. As a result, Ohio officials questioned $200 million in tax dollars spent by the [[Hamilton County, Ohio|Hamiltion County]] Department of Job and Family Services.<ref name ="C Dispatch">{{cite web
|url= http://www.columbusdispatch.com/live/contentbe/EPIC_shim.php?story=213560
|date=2006-09-19
|accessdate = 2008-12-06
|title = "State audit says another $200 million misspent by Hamilton County"
|publisher = [[Columbus Dispatch]]
}}</ref> In 2006, ODJFS took away the license for Lifeway For Youth, a nonprofit Christian-based placement agency, due to the death of a 3 year old boy.
<ref name ="The Cincinnati Enquirer">{{cite web
|url= http://news.cincinnati.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060829/NEWS01/608290337/1056
|date=2006-08-29
|accessdate = 2008-12-06
|title = "Agency had been cited for lax oversight"
|publisher = [[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]
}}</ref> Barb Riley, then the director of ODJFS, questioned "how the private placement agency Lifeway for Youth, [[Butler County, Ohio|Butler County]] Children Services and her own department failed the boy."<ref name ="The Cincinnati Enquirer 2">{{cite web
|url= http://news.cincinnati.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060830/NEWS01/608300355/1056
|date=2006-08-30
|accessdate = 2008-12-06
|title = "Family Services chief orders Marcus probe"
|publisher = [[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]
}}</ref>

For the year 2008, ODJFS sought federal help concerning Ohio<U+2019>s unemployment [[insurance]] [[trust fund]]. State officials had stated that the fund was in danger of running out before the end of the year.<ref name ="Business First of Columbus">{{cite web
|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2008/11/24/daily7.html
|date=2008-11-24
|accessdate = 2008-12-06
|title = "State seeks federal aid for jobless fund"
|publisher = [[American City Business Journals]]
}}</ref> On December 5, 2008, ODJFS announced that extended unemployment compensation benefit payments will start the week of December 22, 2008.<ref name ="Chillicothe Gazette">{{cite web
|url= http://www.chillicothegazette.com/article/20081206/NEWS01/812060308
|date=2008-12-06
|accessdate = 2008-12-06
|title = "ODJFS: Extended jobless benefits to begin Dec. 22"
|publisher = [[Chillicothe Gazette]]
}}</ref> Scarlett Bouder, spokeswoman for the ODJFS, stated that "an estimated 70,000 Ohioans are now eligible for the assistance and thousands more will qualify in the coming weeks as they exhaust their regular benefits."<ref name ="THE COLUMBUS DISPATCH">{{cite web
|url= http://www.dispatchpolitics.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2008/12/05/copy/benefit05.ART_ART_12-05-08_B2_JVC4V63.html?adsec=politics&sid=101
|date=2008-12-05
|accessdate = 2008-12-08
|title = "Agency now has some answers for unemployed"
|publisher = [[Columbus Dispatch]]
}}</ref>

==Director==
[[Helen Jones-Kelley]] was selected to run the ODJFS by Governor-elect [[Ted Strickland]] at the end of 2006.<ref name ="Dayton Daily News">{{cite web
|url= http://www.daytondailynews.com/o/content/oh/story/news/local/2006/12/21/ddn122106kelleyweb.html
|date=2006-12-21
|accessdate = 2008-10-31
|title = "Montgomery County official picked to run state department"
|publisher = [[Dayton Daily News]]
}}</ref> During 2008, Jones-Kelley commented on the jobless rate for Ohio.<ref name ="ABC News">{{cite web
|url= http://abclocal.go.com/wtvg/story?section=news/state&id=5900430
|date=2008-01-18
|accessdate = 2008-10-30
|title = "State jobless rate rises in December"
|publisher = [[ABC News]]
}}</ref> In March of 2008, Jones-Kelley commented that recent news stating that "the [[unemployment rate]] declined slightly must be tempered by the fact that total employment decreased in both goods-producing and service-providing industries."<ref name ="WMFD">{{cite web
|url= http://www.northcentralohio.com/newsboard/single.asp?Story=31214
|date=2008-03-31
|accessdate = 2008-10-30
|title = "Ohio and U.S. Employment Situation (Seasonally Adjusted)"
|publisher = [[WMFD-TV]]
}}</ref> Also, Jones-Kelley commented in May that payroll had fallen and that the economy had remained "sluggish."<ref name ="The Plain Dealer">{{cite web
|url= http://www.cleveland.com/news/plaindealer/index.ssf?/base/news/1211028911184940.xml&coll=2
|date=2008-05-17
|accessdate = 2008-10-30
|title = "More job losses hurt Ohio's economy"
|publisher = [[The Plain Dealer]]
}}</ref>

